## Residual Diagnostics (& Data-Quality Discovery)

- Predicted-vs-actual and residual plots dominated by the more expensive costs (producing skew); zoomed (<$5M) versions added for the bulk of the market
- The single largest test residual (~$96M) traced to a recorded $97.97M sale
    - 2,254 sqft, 4bd/3ba, Oceanside --> ~$43,500/sqft (several times beyond any verified CA sale)
    - second suspect: $48.72M for 1,800 sqft, 3bd/2ba, Encinitas --> ~$27,100/sqft
- Verified against the raw CRMLS extract:
    - ListingKey 1152020272: 
    $97,972,500 close vs $975,000 list --> ×100 unit error (true $979,725, ratio 1.005)
    - ListingKey 1154925192: $48,720,000 close vs $5,150,000 list --> ×10 unit error (true $4,872,000, ratio 0.946)
- Why Week 3's cleaning screen missed them:
    - inspection was bounds-only [$10K, $100M]
        - both rows sat under the ceiling, so they continued uninspected
    - `FACTORS` contained neither ÷10 nor ÷100, so the correct repair hypotheses didn't exist to be tested
- Fix applied in `02_preprocessing.ipynb`:
    - $/sqft plausibility screen (> $15,000/sqft) union-ed with the bounds screen
        - ceiling ~2× above any verified CA residential sale; escapees sat at $27K and $43K
        - rows missing LivingArea can't be evaluated by this screen (documented limitation; handled later in missing values)
    - `FACTORS` extended to `[1, 1e-3, 1e-2, 1e-1, 1e3, 1e6]` — additions are the two proven error magnitudes
- Verdict stability under the wider screen: all 11 original rows kept identical verdicts; new totals 13 inspected / 10 repaired / 1 kept / 2 dropped
    - row count unchanged at 61,604 — two rows converted from "kept corrupt" to "repaired", nothing added or removed
- `03` re-run end-to-end on the regenerated CSV; no modeling code changed

