# 3. Findings

- R² (dollar space), corrected data:
    - raw: train 0.4477 / test 0.4685 / gap −0.0208
    - log: train 0.5425 / test 0.5071 / gap 0.0353
    - **log(ClosePrice) is the Week 5 default; test R² 0.5071 is the number to beat**
- Impact of the two repaired rows (before --> after, log): test R² 0.33 --> 0.5071
    - 2 of 12,007 test rows were suppressing test R² by ~0.17
- Corrected conclusion: the train-test gap originally attributed to market drift was driven almost entirely by the two corrupt test rows
    - drift is real (by-month training residuals climb ~$32K Jan-->Apr; ~9% median rise) but its aggregate effect on test R² is minor (corrected gap 0.035)
    - train R² unchanged by the revision (both rows were in the test month) — coefficients and their interpretation survive untouched
- Negative raw gap (−0.02) unremarkable: train spans five drifting months, test is one
- Window sweep: log spread 0.008 total across X=1–5 (inside single-test-month noise); raw rises mildly with volume (0.4561 --> 0.4685)
    - 4× more training data ≈ no gain --> baseline is bias-limited, not data-limited
    - X = 5 kept (no penalty, maximum data); conclusion is model-specific — re-test with Week 5 models
- Largest residuals post-cleanup belong to genuine $20–35M luxury sales (top of test set: $35M/$31M/$28M/$24M/$22.5M, all coherent: 5,000–12,600 sqft, 5–12 baths, LA/SD)
    - the luxury blindspot is real; its former poster child ($98M) was not

